---

<ArticleLayout
  lang="en"
  animal="dogs"
  title="Dog care guide"
  sidebarItems={sidebarItems}
>

  <!-- ─── FEEDING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="feeding" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">1. Feeding</h2>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2">Diet basics</h3>
    <p>
      Unlike cats, dogs are omnivores — they can digest both meat and plant-based food.
      That said, animal protein should still be the foundation of their diet.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>Dry kibble is the better choice for most dogs.</strong> It is cheaper, lasts longer,
      and — crucially — helps reduce tartar buildup. Wet food is not harmful occasionally,
      but it does nothing for dental health and should not be a regular part of the diet.
      It may be useful short-term for dogs recovering from illness, or those who genuinely
      cannot eat dry food. <strong>Do not mix the two regularly</strong> — mixing encourages
      fussiness and makes it harder to track what your dog is actually eating.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">How to choose dog food</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-1">
      <li>
        <strong>Meat ≥ 60%</strong> — the exact description matters.
        "Chicken" alone is vague; "fresh deboned chicken" tells you what you're actually buying.
        Dogs can develop protein allergies, so observe your dog when switching to a new food.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Read the actual ingredients list</strong> — "complete and balanced" on the label
        can be a marketing claim. What matters is what's actually in the food: the first
        ingredient should be a named animal protein, not a cereal or a generic
        "meat derivative." A brand that publishes a full nutrient breakdown and
        employs a board-certified veterinary nutritionist is a better sign of quality
        than any label slogan.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Carbohydrates matter.</strong> Poor sources (corn, wheat) can cause allergies
        and digestive problems. Better sources: sweet potato, brown rice, peas.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Ignore marketing words</strong> like "holistic," "premium," or "human-grade" —
        these have no legal or nutritional meaning.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm italic text-[#555] dark:text-[#848484]">
      Always read the ingredients list, not just the front of the pack.
      The first three ingredients make up the bulk of the food.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 mb-5 h-75 bg-white dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0] text-sm italic">
      <img class="w-100 dark:hidden" src="/ingridients-dogs.png">
      <img class="w-90 hidden dark:block" src="/ingridients-dogs-dark.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://wsava.org/global-guidelines/global-nutrition-guidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">WSAVA — Global Nutrition Guidelines</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/feeding-your-dog-well-an-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">VCA Hospitals — Feeding your dog</a>
    </p>


    <!-- FORBIDDEN FOODS -->
    <h3 id="forbidden-foods" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Forbidden foods</h3>
    <p>
      Several everyday human foods are toxic to dogs — some severely so. The list below
      covers the most dangerous ones with a short explanation of why each is harmful.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Chocolate, coffee, and caffeine</strong> — contain theobromine and caffeine, which
        dogs break down much more slowly than humans. Even small amounts damage the heart,
        kidneys, and nervous system. Baking chocolate and cocoa powder are the most dangerous.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Grapes, raisins, currants</strong> — cause acute kidney failure. There is
        <em>no safe dose</em> — a single grape can trigger a severe reaction in some dogs.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Xylitol</strong> (sugar-free gum, some peanut butters, medications) — causes
        a massive drop in blood sugar within 30–60 minutes and can lead to liver failure.
        Check peanut butter labels carefully before giving them to your dog.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Onions, garlic, chives, leeks</strong> — in any form (raw, cooked, powdered)
        destroy red blood cells, causing anaemia. Garlic is the most toxic member of this group.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Raw yeast dough</strong> — expands in the stomach (risk of rupture) and
        ferments into alcohol, which is toxic on its own.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Alcohol</strong> — even a small amount causes severe nervous system depression.
        Never leave drinks unattended around dogs.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Macadamia nuts</strong> — cause hind-leg weakness, tremors, and fever.
        Symptoms appear within 12 hours.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Avocado</strong> — the flesh contains persin, which irritates the stomach.
        The pit is a choking hazard.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Salty or very fatty foods</strong> — excessive salt causes sodium poisoning;
        high-fat foods (bacon, fried food) can trigger pancreatitis.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Raw meat and eggs</strong> — carry Salmonella and E. coli. Raw egg whites
        also block absorption of an important B vitamin.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mt-4 font-bold text-[#8b2020] dark:text-[#944040]">
      If you suspect poisoning, call a vet immediately — do not wait for symptoms to develop.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.aspca.org/pet-care/aspca-poison-control/people-foods-avoid-feeding-your-pets" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">ASPCA — Foods to avoid</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4801869/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">NIH/PMC — Household food items toxic to dogs</a>
    </p>


    <!-- TREATS -->
    <h3 id="treats" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Treats</h3>
    <p>
      Treats should make up no more than <strong>10% of your dog's daily calories.</strong>
      For a dog that needs 500 calories a day, that's just 50 calories in treats.
      When giving extra treats, reduce the main meal slightly.
    </p>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Good treat options</h4>
    <p>
      Raw baby carrots (~18 kcal per 50 g), green beans, blueberries, apple slices
      (no seeds), cucumber, and small pieces of plain cooked chicken or turkey are all
      excellent low-calorie options. Your dog's own kibble also makes great training treats —
      it's already nutritionally complete.
    </p>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">What to avoid</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Rawhide — avoid entirely.</strong> It is one of the most popular dog treats
        sold, but also one of the most dangerous. Rawhide is made from the inner layer of
        cow or horse hides, processed with chemicals including sodium sulfide and bleach.
        When chewed, it softens and breaks into large pieces that can cause
        <strong>choking or intestinal blockage</strong> requiring emergency surgery.
        In the stomach it can swell to <strong>four times its original size.</strong>
        It is largely indigestible and offers no nutritional value.
        Safer alternatives for chewing: rubber toys designed for chewing, dried tendons,
        or vet-approved dental chews.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Treats with xylitol, onion, garlic, chocolate, or grapes</strong> — always read
        the full ingredients list on commercial treats before buying.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Large commercial biscuits</strong> — a single big dog biscuit can contain ~85
        calories, more than most small dogs should have in treats for the entire day.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-5 mb-5 h-75 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0] text-sm italic">
      <img  class="w-60" src="/dog-treats.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/dog-treats" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">VCA Hospitals — Dog treats</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://www.vetmed.ucdavis.edu/sites/g/files/dgvnsk491/files/inline-files/treats-guidelines-for-dogs-2020.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">UC Davis Vet Med — Treats guidelines (PDF)</a>
    </p>
  </section>


  <!-- ─── ENVIRONMENT ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="environment" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">2. Environment</h2>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2">Household hazards</h3>
    <p>
      Medications are the most common cause of dog poisoning — ibuprofen, aspirin, and
      vitamins can all be fatal in dog-sized doses. Store all medicines in closed cabinets.
      Other dangers: antifreeze (a quarter cup can kill a medium dog), rat poison
      (some types have no antidote), electrical cords, and loose coins (zinc toxicity).
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Personal space</h3>
    <p>
      Every dog needs a place that is entirely their own — somewhere they can go to rest,
      feel safe, and decompress without being disturbed. This is especially important
      in busy households or for dogs that are anxious. The space should be comfortable,
      quiet, and always accessible. <strong>Never approach or disturb a dog that has
      retreated to their space.</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">Good options include:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-1">
      <li>
        <strong>A dog bed with raised sides or a cave-style bed</strong> — gives a feeling
        of enclosure and security without any door or lock. Many dogs prefer these instinctively.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>A corner with a mat and a blanket</strong> — simple and effective. The dog
        chooses when to go there and when to leave.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Under a table or desk</strong> — dogs often self-select these spots because
        they feel sheltered on three sides. Add a mat to make it official.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>An open travel crate with the door removed</strong> — if you use a crate,
        removing the door entirely turns it into a den rather than a confinement tool.
        The dog can come and go freely and will often choose it voluntarily.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm italic text-[#555] dark:text-[#848484]">
      The goal is a place your dog <em>chooses</em> to be, not a place they are put.
      Forcing a dog into any enclosed space — or locking them in — increases anxiety
      rather than reducing it.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Toxic plants</h3>
    <p>
      Over 1,000 plants are toxic to dogs. The most dangerous are
      <strong>sago palm</strong> (often fatal — causes liver failure),
      <strong>autumn crocus</strong> (organ failure), <strong>oleander</strong> (heart failure),
      and <strong>yew</strong>. Common houseplants like pothos, peace lilies, and English ivy
      cause mouth irritation and vomiting.
      Safe alternatives include sunflowers, petunias, roses, and snapdragons.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 mb-5 h-75 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0] text-sm italic">
      <img  class="w-90" src="/dogs-bed.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.avma.org/resources-tools/pet-owners/petcare/household-hazards" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">AVMA — Household hazards</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://www.aspca.org/pet-care/animal-poison-control/dogs-plant-list" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">ASPCA — Toxic plants list</a>
    </p>
  </section>


  <!-- ─── HYGIENE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="hygiene" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">3. Hygiene</h2>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2">Bathing</h3>
    <p>How often to bathe depends on the coat type. As a general guide:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 mt-1 text-sm">
      <li>Short-haired breeds (Beagle, Greyhound): every <strong>4–8 weeks</strong></li>
      <li>Medium-coated breeds (Golden Retriever, Labrador): every <strong>4–6 weeks</strong></li>
      <li>Long-haired or curly breeds (Poodle, Shih Tzu): every <strong>3–4 weeks</strong></li>
      <li>Hairless breeds (Xolo): every <strong>1–2 weeks</strong> to prevent oil buildup</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-2">
      Never use human shampoo — it has the wrong pH for dog skin and strips protective oils.
      Over-bathing causes dry, itchy skin.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Nails</h3>
    <p>
      Trim nails roughly every <strong>3–4 weeks</strong>. Each nail has a "quick" — a core of blood
      vessels and nerves. Cut about <strong>2–3 mm away from the quick.</strong> For dark nails
      where the quick is invisible, trim tiny 1–2 mm slices until you see a pale grey or pink oval
      in the center — stop there. Keep styptic powder on hand for accidental nicks. Don't forget
      the dewclaws, which can curl painfully into the paw pad if neglected.
      If you hear clicking on hard floors, the nails are overdue.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Ears</h3>
    <p>
      About <strong>20% of dogs have some form of ear disease</strong> — it's the second most
      common reason for vet visits. Floppy-eared breeds (Basset Hounds, Cocker Spaniels) are
      especially prone. Clean at-risk ears every <strong>1–2 weeks</strong> and always after
      swimming or bathing. Use only vet-formulated ear cleaner — never hydrogen peroxide
      or alcohol. Fill the canal, massage the base for 30 seconds, let your dog shake, then
      wipe with cotton.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Teeth</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>About 80% of dogs show signs of gum disease by age 3</strong>, yet only 2% of
      owners brush their dog's teeth. Daily brushing is ideal; 2–3 times per week still makes
      a big difference. Use dog-specific toothpaste (human toothpaste contains xylitol or
      fluoride — both toxic to dogs). Hold the brush at a <strong>45° angle</strong> along the
      gumline and focus on the outer surfaces of the back teeth, where tartar builds fastest.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 mb-5 h-75 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0] text-sm italic">
      <img  class="w-60" src="/dog-teeth.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/how-to-trim-a-dogs-nails" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">VCA Hospitals — Nail trimming</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/instructions-for-ear-cleaning-in-dogs" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">VCA Hospitals — Ear cleaning</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://www.avma.org/resources-tools/pet-owners/petcare/pet-dental-care" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">AVMA — Pet dental care</a>
    </p>
  </section>


  <!-- ─── HEALTH ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="health" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">4. Health</h2>

    <h3 id="sterilization" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Sterilization</h3>
    <p>
      Neutering or spaying your dog brings significant health benefits.
      It eliminates testicular and ovarian cancer, greatly reduces mammary tumour risk,
      and prevents pyometra — a life-threatening uterine infection. Research on over
      <strong>70,000 animals</strong> found that neutered males lived roughly
      <strong>13.8% longer</strong> and spayed females <strong>26.3% longer</strong>
      than intact dogs.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      Traditional timing is <strong>6–9 months</strong>, but for large and giant breeds,
      many vets now recommend waiting until <strong>12–18 months</strong> to allow growth
      plates to close properly, which reduces the risk of certain joint problems.
      Discuss timing with your vet based on your dog's breed and size.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.avma.org/resources-tools/pet-owners/petcare/spaying-and-neutering" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">AVMA — Spaying and neutering</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3629191/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">PMC — Lifespan study (University of Georgia)</a>
    </p>

    <h3 id="parasites" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-8 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Vaccinations &amp; parasite control</h3>
    <p>
      Core vaccines — required for all dogs — cover <strong>distemper, parvovirus, adenovirus,
      rabies, and leptospirosis</strong>. The puppy series starts at <strong>6–8 weeks</strong>,
      with boosters every 3–4 weeks until 16 weeks, then a booster at 1 year, and every
      <strong>3 years</strong> after that. Rabies and leptospirosis are updated <strong>annually</strong>
      (depending on local laws and risk).
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mt-3">
      <li>Deworming starts at <strong>2 weeks of age</strong>, repeated every 2 weeks until 12 weeks, then monthly until 6 months.</li>
      <li>Heartworm prevention starts at <strong>8 weeks</strong> and continues monthly for life.</li>
      <li>Flea and tick treatment begins at <strong>7–8 weeks</strong>, year-round.</li>
      <li>
        Only <strong>5% of a flea infestation lives on the dog</strong> — the other 95%
        (eggs, larvae, cocoons) are in your home environment. Treat the environment too.
      </li>
      <li>Use only <strong>vet-recommended products</strong>. Collars, sprays, and essential oils are unreliable and some are toxic.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.aaha.org/resources/2022-aaha-canine-vaccination-guidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">AAHA — 2022 Canine Vaccination Guidelines</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://capcvet.org/guidelines/general-guidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">CAPC — Parasite prevention guidelines</a>
    </p>
  </section>


  <!-- ─── WALKS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="walks" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">5. Walks &amp; exercise</h2>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2">How much exercise does my dog need?</h3>
    <p>Exercise needs vary enormously by breed, size, and age. A general guide:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 mt-2 text-sm">
      <li>Small breeds (Chihuahua, Pomeranian): <strong>30–60 min/day</strong></li>
      <li>Flat-faced breeds (Pug, Bulldog): <strong>20–30 min/day</strong>, no heat or high intensity</li>
      <li>Medium breeds (Spaniel, Beagle): <strong>30–60 min/day</strong></li>
      <li>Large active breeds (Labrador, Golden Retriever): <strong>60–120 min/day</strong></li>
      <li>Working/herding breeds (Border Collie, Husky): <strong>90–120+ min/day</strong> + mental stimulation</li>
      <li>Giant breeds (Great Dane, Newfoundland): <strong>30–60 min/day</strong>, low-impact preferred</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">
      For puppies, a widely used rule is <strong>5 minutes per month of age</strong>, up to twice
      daily (a 3-month-old gets two 15-minute walks). Large breed puppy bones take up to
      <strong>18–24 months</strong> to fully develop — avoid sustained hard running before then.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Harness vs collar</h3>
    <p>
      For regular walks, a <strong>harness is strongly recommended</strong> over a collar.
      A harness distributes pressure evenly across the chest and shoulders.
      A collar concentrates all force on the throat, which can damage the trachea and
      put pressure on the cervical spine — especially dangerous in dogs that pull.
    </p>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Strict / choke collars — never use them</h4>
    <p>
      Prong collars, choke chains, and slip leads that tighten when pulled cause pain by
      design. They work through punishment, not learning. Beyond being inhumane, they
      risk serious physical injury: tracheal damage, nerve damage in the neck, and in
      some cases have been linked to thyroid problems. There is no situation in which
      a healthy dog requires a collar that causes pain to walk properly.
    </p>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">What about puppies?</h4>
    <p>
      When first teaching a very young puppy to accept a lead, a <strong>flat collar</strong>
      is fine for short introductory sessions indoors or in the garden — the puppy is not
      yet strong enough to pull, and a collar helps them get used to something around
      their neck. As soon as regular outdoor walks begin, transition to a harness.
      All dogs should always wear a flat collar with an ID tag regardless of what equipment
      is used for walking.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-2">
      Front-clip harnesses actively discourage pulling by redirecting the dog's momentum sideways.
      Use a standard-length leash; avoid retractable leashes as they train dogs to pull constantly
      and give little control in emergencies.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-5 mb-2">Off-leash safety</h3>
    <p>
      Only let a dog off-leash once they reliably respond to their name and a recall command
      — tested in increasingly distracting environments. Start indoors, then a fenced yard,
      then a long-line leash (10–50 m) outdoors. Some breeds (sighthounds, scent hounds)
      may never be reliable enough off-leash due to their prey drive. A long-line attached
      to a back-clip harness is a safe compromise.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 mb-5 h-75 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0] text-sm italic">
      <img  class="w-70" src="/dog-harness.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.pdsa.org.uk/pet-help-and-advice/looking-after-your-pet/puppies-dogs/how-much-exercise-does-your-dog-need" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">PDSA — How much exercise does your dog need</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://www.akc.org/expert-advice/training/dog-harness-vs-collar/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">AKC — Harness vs collar</a>
    </p>
  </section>


  <!-- ─── BEHAVIOUR ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="behaviour" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-20">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#D37475] mb-3 pb-1 border-b border-[#e8c4b8]">6. Behaviour</h2>

    <h3 id="play" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Play</h3>
    <p>
      Play isn't optional — it burns energy, reduces stress, and strengthens your bond.
      Fetch, tug-of-war (with clear rules), and puzzle toys are all excellent. Contrary to
      old advice, tug-of-war does <strong>not</strong> cause aggression when you establish rules:
      start and end the game on your terms, and teach a "drop it" command. Around
      <strong>15 minutes with a puzzle toy</strong> is as tiring as a 5 km walk for most dogs.
    </p>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Avoid</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Laser pointers</strong> — can cause obsessive-compulsive behaviour because
        the dog can never actually "catch" the prey. The chasing instinct is activated with
        no satisfying resolution.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Rough wrestling that escalates</strong> — teaches dogs that biting humans
        is acceptable, and can make play sessions harder to control over time.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Small destructible toys unsupervised</strong> — swallowed pieces can cause
        intestinal blockage requiring surgery.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-5 mb-5 h-55 bg-[#f5f0eb] dark:bg-[#454341] border border-dashed border-[#e8c4b8] rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0] text-sm italic">
      <img  class="w-70" src="/dog-toy.png">
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.aspca.org/pet-care/dog-care/common-dog-behavior-issues/play-biting" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">ASPCA — Dog play</a>
    </p>

    <h3 id="alone" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Alone time &amp; separation anxiety</h3>
    <p>
      The RSPCA estimates <strong>8 out of 10 dogs struggle when left alone</strong>, though
      half show no obvious signs. Typical symptoms: destructive chewing, barking, howling,
      house soiling only during absences, and trying to escape. Most anxious behaviour
      occurs within the <strong>first 40 minutes</strong> after you leave.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">The key is <strong>gradual habituation</strong>:</p>
    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2 mt-2">
      <li>
        Start by leaving for <strong>just a few seconds</strong>, return calmly, and gradually
        increase the time over days and weeks.
      </li>
      <li>
        Practise picking up your keys and putting on your coat without leaving —
        this reduces anxiety around departure cues.
      </li>
      <li>
        Give a high-value food puzzle (Kong stuffed with frozen food) <strong>only when you leave</strong>,
        so your dog associates your absence with something positive.
      </li>
      <li>Exercise before leaving — a tired dog is a calmer dog.</li>
      <li>Avoid dramatic goodbyes. Leave and return calmly without a lot of fuss.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-3">
      For severe anxiety that doesn't improve with these methods, speak to a vet — medication
      combined with behavioural work can help significantly.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-[#7a9070] dark:text-[#A9AFA0]">
      Source:
      <a href="https://www.aspca.org/pet-care/dog-care/common-dog-behavior-issues/separation-anxiety" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">ASPCA — Separation anxiety</a>
      ·
      <a href="https://www.rspca.org.uk/adviceandwelfare/pets/dogs/behaviour/separationrelatedbehaviour" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         class="underline hover:text-[#2d5a4e]">RSPCA — Separation-related behaviour</a>
    </p>

    <h3 id="changes" class="font-bold text-xl text-[#774A33] dark:text-[#D49E84] mt-10 mb-2 scroll-mt-20">Introducing changes</h3>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-2 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Switching food</h4>
    <p>Change food gradually over <strong>7 days</strong> to avoid digestive upset:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 mt-1 text-sm">
      <li>Days 1–2: 25% new food, 75% old</li>
      <li>Days 3–4: 50% / 50%</li>
      <li>Days 5–6: 75% new, 25% old</li>
      <li>Day 7: 100% new food</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-4 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Introducing a new dog</h4>
    <p>
      Always do first meetings on <strong>neutral ground</strong> — not your home. Keep both
      dogs on a leash and walk them in parallel with distance between them before gradually
      bringing them closer. Once home, give each dog <strong>separate resources</strong>:
      their own bowl, bed, and toys. Introductions can take weeks of short, supervised
      meetings. Never leave them unsupervised until you're fully confident they're comfortable
      together.
    </p>

    <h4 class="font-semibold mt-4 mb-1 text-[#2d5a4e] dark:text-[#65B9A3]">Socialisation window</h4>
    <p>
      The most critical learning period is between <strong>3 and 14 weeks of age.</strong>
      Puppies exposed to a wide variety of people, animals, environments, sounds, and handling
      during this window grow into calmer, more confident adults. The AVSAB notes that
      <strong>behavioural problems — not diseases — are the leading cause of death in dogs
      under 3 years.</strong> Puppy classes can start after at least 2 vaccinations
      (around 11–12 weeks).
    </p>

